y the tent. I rose up on one elbow and looked about the interior of the tent. I had to smile – it was so very much the domain of the man for whom it was made. Velvet cushions were thick about the floor, strange symbols glowing upon their surfaces. The dark smell of myrrh rose from the cushions wherever I touched them, surrounding me like an opiate cloud. My usual armor had been replaced by a gown of silvery cloth – like that of a spider’s web when the sunlight strikes its dew-covered frame. My feet were clad in silver sandals; my hair in long dark braids lay strewn across the cushions.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
My lord had been called into the very stronghold of Cazic Thule’s temple to assist those who had accompanied us to hear our vows. As the sounds of the battle filtered mutedly into the tent, he bowed his head and his lips gently brushed my forehead.<br>
<br>
“My lady, I must go,” he said quietly. “I shall return to your side before the night passes its darkest point.”<br>
<br>
There was a shimmer of light and the tent flap fell closed. Outside, I heard a few hushed words and the soft sound of bone fragments as they settled, scattered, in the cool damp grass of the jungle.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
The sound of the tent’s heavy flap being pushed aside awoke me again some time later. The oil lamp that hung from the apex of the covering canopy flickered slowly in a slight, cool breeze. Its odd shape cast more shadow than light about the tent. One of these shades stepped forward, and its form resolved into that of my lord and master, his blazing eyes melting my own. His skin glowed the blue of a moonless midnight, a soft dusting of iridescent scales falling sparkling from his hair as he moved.<br>
<br>
There were times when he was so powerful as to be painful if too close – the power of himself and all the souls he had pulled to him. My eyes hurt if I looked at him too long when he was so, and the burning touch of his hand left its mark on me for weeks.<br>
<br>
He knelt beside me, his hand hot against my cheek, caressing it. My skin tingled under his touch. “My lady.” I sat up, arms embracing him, pulling him close to me. “My love,” I whispered, my lips smiling, brushing against his neck.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
The sun was rising in the sky when I laid my head upon his shoulder, letting sleep overcome me… The wind through the trees whispered softly as my eyes closed.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
(An old story of Humwawa and Taerma, from the day we were married on the steps of Cazic Thule) <p>Taerma D'Estain<br>
